Q)Given two Strings , write a method to decide if one is permutation of the other.
Approach Explanation:

Key Observation

Two strings are permutations of each other if and only if:

They contain the same characters

With the same frequencies

Order does not matter

âœ… Approach 1: Sorting Based Comparison
Idea

If two strings are permutations, then after sorting, they will become identical.

Sorting rearranges characters into a fixed order, making comparison easy.

Steps

Convert each string to a character array

Sort both arrays

Compare the sorted strings

If equal â†’ permutation exists
code 1:
import java.util.Scanner;
import java.util.Arrays;
public class Main
{
    public static String sort(String s){
        char[] c = s.toCharArray();
        Arrays.sort(c);
        int n = c.length;
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            sb.append(c[i]);
        }
        return sb.toString();
        
    }
	public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        String s1 = sc.nextLine();
        String s2 = sc.nextLine();
        if(sort(s1).equals(sort(s2))){
            System.out.println("Yes");
            return ;
        }
        System.out.println("No");
	}
}
Time Complexity

Sorting string 1: O(n log n)

Sorting string 2: O(n log n)

Comparison: O(n)

ðŸ‘‰ Overall Time Complexity:
O(n log n)

Space Complexity

Character arrays + StringBuilder

O(n) extra space
code 2:
Idea

Permutations must have exactly the same character counts

Since strings contain characters, we can use a frequency array

Increment for first string, decrement for second

If all counts become zero â†’ permutation

Steps

Create a frequency array of size 128 (ASCII characters)

Traverse first string â†’ increment counts

Traverse second string â†’ decrement counts

Check if all values are zero
import java.util.Scanner;
public class Main
{
	public static void main(String[] args) {
		Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
		String s1 = sc.nextLine();
		String s2 = sc.nextLine();
		int[] freq = new int[128];

        for (char c : s1.toCharArray()) {
            freq[c]++;
        }
        for (char c : s2.toCharArray()) {
            freq[c]--;
        }
        for(int i=0;i<128;i++){
            if(freq[i]>0 || freq[i]<0){
                System.out.println("No");
                return ;
            }
        }
		System.out.println("Yes");
	}
}
Time Complexity

Traversing string 1: O(n)

Traversing string 2: O(n)

Checking frequency array: O(1) (fixed size 128)

ðŸ‘‰ Overall Time Complexity:
O(n)

Space Complexity

Frequency array of fixed size (128)

O(1) extra space
